&gt; Max-Age=\&lt;number&gt;
&gt;
&gt; Indicates the number of seconds until the cookie expires. A zero or negative number will expire the cookie immediately. If both Expires and Max-Age are set, Max-Age has precedence.

Make sure that other attributes (i.e. `Path`) are set correctly: if the client&#39;s cookie is set with `Path=/`, the server should set that same value before sending the cookie. Same goes for the other attributes.

This is how I have done it, in Go:
```lang-go
// Taken from the handler that logs users in:
session_id := generateRandomString()
cookie := &amp;http.Cookie{
	Name:     &quot;session&quot;,
	Value:    session_id,
	MaxAge:   int(time.Hour.Seconds()),
	Secure:   r.TLS != nil, // r is the typical *http.Request
	HttpOnly: true,
	SameSite: http.SameSiteStrictMode,
	Path:     &quot;/&quot;,
}
http.SetCookie(w, cookie)
```
```lang-go
// Taken from the handler that logs users out:
cookie, err := r.Cookie(&quot;session&quot;)
if err != nil {
	http.Error(w, &quot;cookie not found&quot;, http.StatusUnauthorized)
	return
}
// Here goes the logic to log out the user.
// Once that is done, it is time to send an expired cookie back:
newCookie := &amp;http.Cookie{
	Name:     &quot;session&quot;,
	Value:    cookie.Value,
	MaxAge:   -1,
	Secure:   r.TLS != nil,
	HttpOnly: true,
	SameSite: http.SameSiteStrictMode,
	Path:     &quot;/&quot;,
}
http.SetCookie(w, newCookie)
```

From Go&#39;s source code for type `Cookie`:

```lang-go
// MaxAge=0 means no &#39;Max-Age&#39; attribute specified.
