answers.body_markdown:
Since `DataConfig` is not a subtype or supertype of `LinkedHashMap`, casting cannot be used there. Im not familiar with yaml, but I can assume that the method `yaml.load()` returns a `LinkedHashMap` from your exception description.

Try writing a static method belonging to `DataConfig` that converts a `LinkedHashMap` to a `DataConfig`:

    public static DataConfig parseNew(LinkedHashMap map) {

    }

To solve this, you should add a [TypeDescription][1] to your ***Yaml*** object and manually map the type of the list of the underlying property:

    yaml.addTypeDescription(new TypeDescription(DataConfig.class) {
        @Override
        public boolean setupPropertyType(String key, Node valueNode) {
            if (&quot;heros&quot;.equals(key) &amp;&amp;  valueNode instanceof MappingNode) {
                MappingNode mappingNode = (MappingNode) valueNode;
                boolean listTypeDefined = false;
                for (NodeTuple nodeTuple : mappingNode.getValue()) {
                    if (nodeTuple.getValueNode() instanceof SequenceNode) {
                        SequenceNode sequenceNode = (SequenceNode) nodeTuple.getValueNode();
                        sequenceNode.setListType(Data.class);
                        listTypeDefined = true;
                    }
                }
                return listTypeDefined;
            }
            return super.setupPropertyType(key, valueNode);
        }
    });

If you do this and run your program, you should see the following output:

    one h1
    two h3
    Test$DataConfig@6a79c292

Please note a small mistake in your example, your ***Data*** class has a property ***url*** whereas in the yaml it&#39;s ***uri***.

  [1]: https://github.com/snakeyaml/snakeyaml/blob/master/src/main/java/org/yaml/snakeyaml/TypeDescription.java

